properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert: Widespread Overland Flooding
properties.Summary:
Description: Lac Ste. Anne County is experiencing significant widespread overland flooding in many area as a result of a sudden spring melt and warmer temperatures. As well, rapid snow melt continues to seriously impact the rising water levels of both the Little Paddle and Paddle Rivers. Paddle River dykes are over topping at this time. ### Residents and the travelling public will encounter high water levels in roadside ditches, and water encroaching or crossing on many area roadways, including highways. Residents along the Little Paddle and Paddle Rivers will continue to see additional overland flooding of low lying areas in the coming days.
Expires: 2020-04-26T11:18:14-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Lac Ste. Anne County, 2020-04-19T11:17:05-06:00, NAADS-CA-AB-AEA1-6318
Area: Lac Ste. Anne County
properties.Author: Lac Ste. Anne County

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Late season snowfall on tap tonight and Tuesday. Showers and flurries are expected to change over to snow tonight as much colder air from the arctic blasts into Northeastern Ontario in the wake of a strong low pressure system. Snow will continue on Tuesday as the low moves slowly into Western Quebec. Most areas will receive a total of near 10 cm of snow by Tuesday evening. The highest snowfall amounts will be near the Quebec border where total amounts close to 15 cm are expected. Strong and gusty northwesterly winds will result in low visibility at times in blowing snow especially Tuesday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-04-21T11:46:57-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-04-20T19:47:57-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1152450356.2020

properties.Title: Update: Ice Pile Up On The South Shores Of Lake Winnipeg, Lake Manitoba, Lake Winnipegosis And Dauphin Lake.
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre is reporting high winds will create a moderate to high risk of ice pile up on the south shores of Lake Winnipeg (including areas near Gimli and Victoria Beach), Lake Manitoba, Lake Winnipegosis, and Dauphin Lake throughout the afternoon and evening of April 20, 2020. Residents in the affected area should take immediate actions to protect yourself and property. Follow all directions by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding, follow @MBGov on Twitter or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2020-04-20T22:00:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2020-04-20T11:30:13-05:00, 2651BAFF-5616-253E-A21D-BCE068E8224B
Area: South shores of Lake Winnipeg, Lake Manitoba, Lake Winnipegosis, and Dauphin Lake.

If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A variety of wintry precipitation is expected. Locations: Avalon Peninsula. Time span: Tuesday. Total rainfall: less than 2 mm (northwestern Avalon) to 20 mm (parts of the southeastern Avalon). Total snowfall: less than 2 cm (southeastern Avalon) to 10 cm (parts of the northwestern Avalon). Remarks: Precipitation is forecast to begin over the southern Avalon on Tuesday morning and will spread to northern areas by noon. Over southeastern parts of the peninsula, the precipitation will fall mostly as rain, while over northwestern areas, mainly snow is expected. Areas in between, including the St. John's Metro area, can expect a messy variety of rain, freezing rain, ice pellets and snow. There is potential for localized significant snowfall, especially across higher elevations on the northern Avalon. Conditions will improve Tuesday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-04-21T10:26:02-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-04-20T18:27:02-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0928900505.2020
Area: Avalon Peninsula North, Avalon Peninsula Southeast, St. John's and vicinity, Avalon Peninsula Southwest

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 25 to 30 cm is expected. Moisture streaming eastward across the northern Yukon is generating snow at times heavy over northern sections of the Dempster region. An additional 5 cm of snow is expected near the Richardson Mountains through this morning. The heaviest snow is expected to ease by this afternoon, though periods of snow are expected to continue into Tuesday morning. Gusty winds combined with falling snow will lead to local blowing snow this morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
